Monday, December 29, 2025

What 160+ Projects Taught Me About Working with Claude

I've built 160+ things in the last year. Web apps, games, developer tools, educational platforms, visualizations. Some took an afternoon. Some took weeks. Most of them involved AI assistance in some form.

Around project 80 or so, I started noticing patterns. By project 100, I had strong opinions. Now, after spending the last month deep in Claude Code with Opus 4.5, I think I finally understand what actually matters.

This isn't about feelings. This is about what I've learned.

The First Lesson: Get Out of the Way

Early on, I over-engineered everything. Elaborate prompts. Detailed specifications. Step-by-step instructions that read like legal documents.

It didn't help. Sometimes it made things worse.

The Claude Code team has this philosophy: write as little business logic as possible. Let the model do its thing. Every time there's a new model release, they delete code rather than add it. With Opus 4.5, they deleted half the system prompt because it wasn't needed anymore.

I've started doing the same. My prompts got shorter. My context got cleaner. I stopped trying to anticipate every edge case upfront.

The result? Better output. Faster iteration. Less friction.

There's a concept in AI called "product overhang." It means the model can already do something, but the product around it isn't built to capture that capability. I was creating my own product overhang by getting in the way.

The Second Lesson: Prototype Like It's Free

Here's something that changed my approach completely.

The Claude Code team built 20 different prototypes of their todo list feature in two days. Twenty. Not variations on a theme. Twenty genuinely different approaches. They tried showing todos inline, in a drawer, as a pill, above the input, with animation, without. Each prototype took maybe 30 minutes.

That's not how I used to work. I used to think through everything first, pick the best approach, then build it once. Because building was expensive.

Building isn't expensive anymore.

When I built the Daily AI News Scan, I tried three completely different architectures in one afternoon. Email workers vs. scheduled functions vs. webhook triggers. Each one took about an hour to prototype. By dinner, I knew which one worked best. Not because I thought really hard about it. Because I tried all of them.

This changes how you make decisions. You stop asking "which approach is theoretically best?" and start asking "which approach actually works?" Big difference.

The Third Lesson: Structure Beats Prompting

I used to think the secret was in the prompts. Write better prompts, get better results.

That's maybe 20% of it.

The other 80% is context. What files does the model have access to? How is your codebase organized? What patterns exist that it can learn from?

When I built COMPASS, my coding standards framework for AI systems, the goal was to give Claude consistent context across all my projects. Same principles, same patterns, same expectations. Now when Claude works on any of my 160+ projects, it already knows how I think about security, testing, and code organization.

That single decision, creating a shared context document, improved my results more than any prompting technique I've tried.

The model is smart enough. Your job is to give it the right information to work with.

The Fourth Lesson: Small Bets Compound

My whole philosophy is "small bets." Ship fast, learn faster, don't get attached to any single outcome.

Turns out this aligns perfectly with AI-assisted development.

When the cost of trying something drops to near zero, you can run more experiments. More experiments means more learning. More learning compounds into better intuition. Better intuition means you know what to try next.

I didn't plan to build 160+ projects. I just kept making small bets, and they accumulated. Each one taught me something. A new API. A tricky edge case. A pattern that worked. A pattern that didn't.

By project 50, I had intuitions I couldn't have gotten any other way. By project 100, I could look at a problem and know roughly how to approach it, because I'd probably seen something similar before.

The AI accelerated the building. But the real value was in the accumulated knowledge from all that building.

The Fifth Lesson: Trust Calibration Takes Time

How much should you trust the model? This is the question everyone asks.

The honest answer: it depends, and you have to learn it through experience.

After 160+ projects, I have a feel for where Claude excels and where it struggles. It's great at boilerplate, patterns, and well-documented APIs. It's less reliable with cutting-edge libraries, niche domains, and anything where the training data is sparse.

It will confidently tell you wrong things sometimes. That's not a flaw, it's a characteristic you need to account for.

My approach now: trust by default, verify at the boundaries. Let it write the code. Check the parts that interact with external systems, handle user input, or touch data persistence. These are where mistakes have consequences.

This isn't something you can learn from a blog post. You have to build things, see where it breaks, and update your mental model. Repeatedly.

The Sixth Lesson: Speed Changes What's Possible

There's a qualitative shift that happens when iteration gets fast enough.

When building something takes days, you think carefully before starting. You plan. You spec. You try to get it right the first time because rework is expensive.

When building something takes hours, you just try stuff. Ideas that would have been "interesting but not worth the time" become "let's see if this works."

The Daily AI News Scan was an idea I had in the shower. Two weeks ago, that idea would have gone on a list of "things to maybe build someday." Instead, I had a working prototype by lunch. It's been running in production ever since.

I'm willing to follow hunches now. To chase weird ideas. To try things that probably won't work. Because the cost of finding out is so low.

Not all of those hunches pay off. But some do. And the ones that do wouldn't have happened if I'd been more careful.

The Seventh Lesson: The Model Keeps Getting Better

Every few months, there's a step change.

Opus 4.5 is meaningfully better than what came before. Not just faster or cheaper. Better at understanding what I actually want. Better at maintaining context across long sessions. Better at catching its own mistakes.

The Claude Code team says they delete code with each model release. I've started doing the same with my expectations. Things that didn't work six months ago work now. Approaches I gave up on deserve another try.

This is important because it means the patterns I've learned aren't permanent. They're calibrated to current capabilities. As the model improves, I need to recalibrate.

The best approach isn't to learn a fixed set of techniques. It's to stay curious, keep experimenting, and update your mental model as capabilities change.

What I Actually Believe Now

After 160+ projects, here's what I think matters:

Context over prompting. Give the model good information to work with. Don't try to be clever with your instructions.

Iteration over specification. Build fast prototypes and learn from them. Don't over-plan.

Trust calibration through experience. You can't shortcut this. Build things, see what breaks, adjust.

Small bets compound. Each project teaches you something. The accumulated learning is more valuable than any single project.

Get out of the way. The model is more capable than you think. Stop over-engineering and let it work.

None of this is revolutionary. Most of it sounds obvious when you say it out loud.

But there's a difference between knowing these things intellectually and having them in your bones from building, constantly building. The former is information. The latter is intuition.

And developing that intuition, how humans can work together with AI, is for me the biggest takeaway working with Claude and other AIs.

2025 Victor del Rosal
